    parentName: "p"
  }, "The beauty of music is the beauty of mathematics, perceived in real time.")), mdx("p", null, "We see this in its visual manifestations all the time. The ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catenary"
  }, "curve"), " of the cables of the Golden Gate Bridge, the ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2013/06/scienceshot-sunflowers-do-math"
  }, "pattern of seeds"), " in the sunflower, the ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "http://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap120916.html"
  }, "rings of Saturn"), " \u2014 all clear manifestations of the way the universe works, that can be described by math, and that we find beautiful."), mdx("p", null, "Music presents a pure, distilled form of this: beauty created by small, whole numbers and their relationships to each other."), mdx("h2", {
    "id": "notes-and-intervals"
  }, "Notes and Intervals"), mdx("p", null, "A note, in music, is a sound with a particular pitch. Pitch is frequency, measured in cycles per second, or Hertz (Hz). The faster the vibration, the higher the pitch."), mdx("p", null, "A vibration, at, say, 220 Hz, all by itself is a note by that general definition. But the note doesn\u2019t acquire its distinct personality until it\u2019s considered in relation to some other note. That relationship is called an interval."), mdx("p", null, "Here is that 220 Hz note, played on a cello, all by itself: ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "/blog/13855ef75ab8577cde131040c255fd6e/220-Hz.mp3"
  }, "220 Hz")), mdx("p", null, "Here it is in relation to a note an octave below, vibrating half as fast, at 110 Hz: ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "/blog/35464c315d241212d2a94e4d760f3ab4/Octave.mp3"
  }, "220 and 110")), mdx("p", null, "It still sounds like the same note. But now play it with a note vibrating at 1/3 of its frequency, or 73.33 Hz. The 220 Hz note acquires a very different character: ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "/blog/c3890c8e8482715bd954ec9be34207a4/Fifth.mp3"
  }, "220 and 73")), mdx("p", null, "And now with a note at 1/5 its frequency, 44 Hz: ", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "/blog/01bd757294637d13bbb7ec7a42087bf4/Third.mp3"
  }, "220 and 44")), mdx("p", null, "Even though the 220 Hz note always has the same pitch, in a different context it has a different personality and function."), mdx("p", null, "The lattice of the Flying Dream video does not show absolute pitch. Each intersection, or node, represents a note, named according to its relationship to one special note: the Tonic."), mdx("h2", {
    "id": "the-tonic"
  }, "The Tonic"), mdx("p", null, "The heart of the lattice is the note called 1. This note is the tonic."), mdx("p", null, mdx("span", {
