    "href": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consonance_and_dissonance"
  }, "Consonance and dissonance"), " are descriptions of feelings; they are part of the flavor of an interval, and I don\u2019t think the last word has been written on them yet. I\u2019ll be taking my shot later in these pages.)"), mdx("p", null, "For very small ratios such as 3/2, the ear has no trouble perceiving where it is on the map. The signal given by 3/2 is so strong, in fact, that it\u2019s the primary tool used in classical music to move the ear to a new key center."), mdx("p", null, "As the numbers get bigger, the signal gets weaker, and the interval gets more dissonant. To get to the major second, you multiply by 3 twice. Then, using octave reduction, you can put it in any octave you want. I chose 9:4 in yesterday\u2019s example, giving an interval of a major ninth \u2014 an octave plus a major second."), mdx("p", null, "Compounding a fifth and a third gives somewhat larger numbers (3\xD75 = 15, or a ratio of 15/8) and, sure enough, the note is more dissonant against the tonic. Yet it has its own unique beauty. Presenting the major seventh:"), mdx("p", null, mdx("a", {
