    "href": "http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/if-the-mountain-will-not-come-to-muhammad.html"
  }, "The mountain has come to Muhammad"), "."), mdx("p", null, "The ratio of the perfect fourth is 1/3. This can be octave-reduced (octave-expanded) by moving it up two octaves, to 4/3."), mdx("p", null, "The energy of the fourth, the division energy, has had a number of names. Harry Partch, a major composer and explorer of music in just intonation, called the quality of the right-and-up harmonies (the ones you get to by multiplication) otonality, from overtone. He called the energy of division-based harmony utonality, for undertone."), mdx("p", null, "Once again I\u2019m going with Mathieu on this one. In Harmonic Experience, he gives an excellent rationale for calling this energy reciprocal. I think he\u2019s right. Each overtonal note has its mirror twin, and the twins are identical, just upside down from each other \u2014 reciprocals. The fourth is the reciprocal of the fifth."), mdx("h2", {
    "id": "mixed-messages"
  }, "Mixed Messages"), mdx("p", null, "The harmonic lattice can be divided into four quadrants."), mdx("p", null, "Northeast is pure overtonal energy. All these notes are reached by multiplication alone. Powers of 3 and 5 are in the numerators, and the denominators are all powers of 2."), mdx("p", null, "Southwest is pure reciprocal energy. You get there by dividing. All the 3\u2019s and 5\u2019s are on the bottom of the ratio (or fraction), and the powers of 2 are on the top."), mdx("p", null, "Northwest is mixed reciprocal and overtonal energy. You multiply by fives and divide by threes."), mdx("p", null, "Southeast is also mixed. Multiply by threes and divide by fives."), mdx("p", null, "The major sixth is in the northwest quadrant. First divide the tonic by 3, which gives you a perfect fourth. Then multiply that by 5, and you get the major sixth. Its ratio is 5/3. You can do this in any order, of course \u2014 multiplying by 5 gets you to the major third, and dividing by 3 brings you to the sixth again."), mdx("p", null, mdx("a", {
