  }, "The Minor Seventh"), mdx("p", null, "The farther we get from the center, the less consonant the notes are, when played against the tonic. Consonance is a whole subject. It\u2019s generally spoken of as though it could be plotted on a scale, from consonance to dissonance. I think this is a big mistake. Consonance has more than one dimension. Trying to force these independent dimensions of consonance onto a one-dimensional scale leads to unnecessary confusion."), mdx("p", null, "Anywayy \u2026 The minor seventh is a pretty dissonant note in all dimensions. It\u2019s three moves away from the tonic, down a third and up two fifths:"), mdx("p", null, mdx("a", {
