  }, "Untempered Vs. Tempered"), mdx("p", null, "I\u2019ve been listening to yesterday\u2019s chord progression showing off the b7."), mdx("p", null, "I think it offers an excellent opportunity to hear the difference between equal temperament and just intonation."), mdx("p", null, "Equal temperament works by implying or evoking a note rather than playing it exactly. There are dozens of singable notes per octave; ET represents them all with just twelve tones."), mdx("p", null, "Some ET notes are close to their just counterparts; the 4 and 5 are close enough to be essentially right on. The major third is not so great. It\u2019s 0.8% sharp, enough to change the feeling it produces."), mdx("p", null, "The ET b7 is even further off, a full 1% flat of the untempered note. For me, this is enough to change its flavor entirely, and dilute its resonance to the point where it\u2019s just not the same note. I would contend that the real experience of the b7 is not actually available in equal temperament."), mdx("p", null, "Here it is again:"), mdx("p", null, mdx("a", {
